article.headline: Minnesota 93, Southern 41
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- If Minnesota's season-opener is any
indication, it's going to be a fast-break kind of year for the
Gophers.

Lindsay Whalen had 27 points, seven rebounds and four assists as
13th-ranked Minnesota ran its transition offense to near perfection
in a 93-41 victory over Southern in the Subway Classic. The Gophers
will face No. 16 Colorado, an 85-81 winner over Harvard, in
Sunday's title game.

"I just wanted our team to get out there and play hard," said
Minnesota coach Pam Borton. "Any fast-break opportunity we get, we
have to push it down people's throats. If we pull the reins back,
we're not playing our game. We have to make sure we're getting
better every game."

Whalen kicked off her senior year by making 10 of 13 shots, and
she scored 17 points while the Gophers built a 49-18 halftime lead.
Whalen's backcourt mate, sophomore Shannon Schonrock, tied a career
high with 12 points, all coming in the first half, and dished out a
game-high six assists.

Whalen and Schonrock ran wild in the first half, scoring 17 of
the team's first 19 points, then hitting back-to-back fast-break
layups to cap a 13-0 spurt that put Minnesota (1-0) ahead 29-8.

"We put a lot of emphasis on that in practice," Schonrock
said. "I think we're at our best when we run."

The Gophers shot 58.6 percent from the floor and had 24 assists
as a team. They also outrebounded Southern 43-29, with junior
center Janel McCarville triggering numerous fast-break
opportunities with long outlet passes after rebounds.

"Everything was created by our defensive rebounding," Whalen
said. "It's fun to get out and run, get layups and easy baskets,
and it's fun to watch."

Whalen made sure of that with the best of many fine Minnesota
passes. Taking an outlet pass from McCarville, she drove to the
hoop, then hit freshman Kelly Roysland in stride with a
behind-the-back pass. Roysland was fouled on the play.

"I'm just sorry I couldn't finish it," said Roysland, who
scored 16 points in her collegiate debut. "I was thinking she'd
take it all the way and finish it herself because she's so good at
finishing. I didn't want her to throw a good pass and have it roll
off my leg.

"It's typical of how unselfish a player Lindsay is," Roysland
said. "She put her trust in me as a freshman, and was confident
that I could finish the play."

Minnesota held the Jaguars to 28.8 percent shooting and forced
19 turnovers. They also maintained their intensity in the second
half after finishing flat in a pair of preseason games.

"We know once we get up on a team and get the knife in them, we
have to be able to twist it," Schonrock said.

Rolanda Monroe led Southern (0-1) with 17 points.
